				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X + Y + Z = 1$$\end{document}. This should take into account the interaction between the different constituents of the gas, including partial ionization. Also, pressure and internal energy from radiation must be included, although they play a comparatively minor role in the Sun. An important constraint on the treatment is that it be thermodynamically consistent such that all thermodynamic relations are satisfied between the computed quantities (e.g., Däppen 1993). Thus it would not, for example, be consistent to add the contribution of Coulomb effects to pressure and internal energy without making corresponding corrections to other quantities, including the thermodynamical potentials that control the ionization.

