				\begin{document}$$6 \times 10^{10}\,\,\mathrm{cm}^{-2}\,\,\mathrm{s}^{-1}$$\end{document}. It is evident that the detection of this neutrino flux would be a strong confirmation of the importance of nuclear reactions in the core of the present Sun, and potentially a very valuable diagnostics of conditions in the solar core. Here I provide a brief overview of some key aspects and results of the study of solar neutrinos. More detailed reviews of solar neutrino studies have been given by Bahcall (1989), Haxton (1995), Castellani et al. (1997), Kirsten (1999) and Turck-Chièze (1999); Bahcall and Peña Garay (2004) and McDonald (2004) have provided reviews on the theoretical and experimental situation, respectively, and general overviews were given by Haxton et al. (2006, 2013) and Haxton (2008).

