A second type of neutrino experiment uses neutrino scattering on electrons in water, causing Čerenkov light from the resulting energetic electrons. Since the electrons are predominantly scattered in the forward direction the detection is sensitive to the direction of the incoming neutrinos, effectively producing a ‘neutrino image’ of the Sun, albeit with low resolution. Great care is taken to purify the water in the detector and shield it from background radiation, including active background detection in a surrounding volume of water. Even so, owing to the dominant background at lower energies, these experiments are limited to neutrino energies above a few MeV. i.e., to the 8B\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
