				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{}^{3}\mathrm{He}}$$\end{document} abundance on the solar surface was strongly increased in the mass-losing models, but they did not consider the available observations sufficiently secure to rule out such models. Swenson and Faulkner (1992) considered mass loss as an explanation of the observed lithium abundances in the Sun and in the Hyades cluster. In the solar case, they found that the observed present solar lithium abundance could be accounted for with an initial solar mass of 1.1M⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
