				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$1.1 \,M_\odot $$\end{document} and either exponentially decreasing or constant mass loss. A similar conclusion had been reached by Boothroyd et al. (1991).

The availability of detailed helioseismic data obviously provides further constraints on the mass-losing models. Guzik and Cox (1995) compared models with a total loss of 0.1M⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
